'''Machine operator efficiency''' (MOE) is a [[lean manufacturing]] term used to describe the performance of an employee who operates industrial machinery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Do You Know MOE|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/machine-operator-efficiency-moe-rick-wenzel?trk=pulse_spock-articles|publisher=LinkedIn}}</ref> The operator's efficiency is measured as the time spent producing product divided by the time the operator is on duty.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sarkar|first1=Prasanta|title=How to calculate operator efficiency at work|url=http://www.onlineclothingstudy.com/2011/09/how-to-calculate-operator-efficiency.html|publisher=OCS|date=2011-09-23|accessdate=2015-09-27}}</ref> For example: if an operator is assigned to run a CNC machine tool for seven hours, but he only has four hours worth of continuous uninterrupted output of workpieces - his MOE rating is 57% (4 divided by 7) for this seven-hour period of time.

There is a similar lean manufacturing [[Key Performance Indicator|KPI]] called [[overall equipment effectiveness]] (OEE). The major difference between OEE and MOE is that the OEE rating is on the machine and the MOE is on the person.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}

MOE is a measure of operator performance only, regardless of the type of machine or the speed of the machine he is working on. MOE only measures the operator's ability to keep the machine running continuously (load and unload parts faster that the automatic cycle time of the machine). The MOE rating of an operator will travel with him as he moves from one machine to another. This is easily accomplished because the MOE rating is a universal calculation of time and not reliant on the complex OEE calculations of loading, availability, performance, and quality.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}

[[Industrial dashboard|Industrial Dashboards]] can be used to display statistics for MOE ratings on each operator. To boost overall profitability for a manufacturing plant, machine operators are sometimes compensated with a salary bonus based on their MOE ratings.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}

