{{Orphan|date=December 2012}}
The '''Lewis model of economic growth''' analyses the process of [[economic expansion]] in a [[dual economy]]. [[W.A Lewis]] put forward his views systematically in his article "Economic Development with Unlimited Supplies of Labor"<ref>{{cite book|last=misra|first=puri|title=Economics of development and planning|year=2010|publisher=Himalaya publishing house|location=mumbai|isbn=978-81-8488-829-4|pages=263}}</ref> Lewis divides the economy of an underdeveloped country into two sectors:
'''The [[Capitalist]] Sector:''' Defined as "that part of the economy which uses reproducible capital and pays capitalists thereof". The use of capital is controlled by the capitalists, who hire the services of [[Manual labour|labor]]. It includes [[manufacturing]], [[plantation]]s, [[mining|mines]], etc.
